The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                               BRIEFS
                  
	Durgapur, June 13: The state pollution watchdog has slapped a closure order on Durgapur Projects Limiteds coke oven plant for discharging toxic effluents into the Damodar despite warnings.     
	The directive seeks to close down the state-owned plant, which employs around 1,700 people, by June 21. A DPL spokesperson, however, said the matter would be sorted out through talks on Monday.        
	Midnapore: Suspected Maoists shot dead a leader of an anti-Naxalite outfit that is backed by the CPM in West Midnapore. Shankar Tudu, 48, was sipping tea at a roadside stall in Bhulaveda when five men shot him down.         
	Calcutta: Four goldsmiths, who were returning home from Delhi, were found unconscious on the Howrah-bound Kalka Mail on Friday after they were allegedly drugged and robbed by co-passengers who offered them mangoes and biscuits. They were robbed of jewellery and cash worth Rs 1.5 lakh.        
	Burdwan: Police lathicharged and threw tear gas shells when 5,000 Trinamul Congress workers surrounded the Burdwan sadar police station to protest the arrest of their leader Ramdas Mondal. The party general secretary of Burdwan was arrested from Nizam Palace in Calcutta on Friday. He is wanted in two murder cases and seven other cases.                                                                                                                                                                       
